citation_title: Mefloquine targets the Plasmodium falciparum 80S ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.

pfam_comments: This family is found at the very C-terminal of 60 ribosomal L4 proteins.
This family includes Ribosomal L4/L1 from eukaryotes and archaebacteria and L4 from eubacteria. L4 from yeast has been shown to bind rRNA [1].
This region is found associated with Pfam:PF00281.

This family includes: Ribosomal L7A from metazoa, Ribosomal L8-A and L8-B from fungi, 30S ribosomal protein HS6 from archaebacteria, 40S ribosomal protein S12 from eukaryotes, Ribosomal protein L30 from eukaryotes and archaebacteria. Gadd45 and MyD118 [1].
This family includes the eukaryotic ribosomal protein L14.
This family includes higher eukaryotic ribosomal 60S L27A, archaeal 50S L18e, prokaryotic 50S L15, fungal mitochondrial L10, plant L27A, mitochondrial L15 and chloroplast L18-3 proteins.

This family contains the large 60S ribosomal L5 proteins from Eukaryota and the 50S L18 proteins from Archaea. It has been shown that the amino terminal 93 amino acids of Swiss:P09895 are necessary and sufficient to bind 5S rRNA in vitro [1], suggesting that the entire family has a function in rRNA binding [2,3,4,5].
This domain is the C-terminal end of ribosomal L18/L5 proteins.
pfam_descriptions: Ribosomal large subunit proteins 60S L5, and 50S L18

pfam_comments: This family includes: archaeal 50S ribosomal protein L18Ae, often referred to as L20e or LX; fungal 60S ribosomal protein L20; and higher eukaryote 60S ribosomal protein L18A.
This family includes L22 from prokaryotes and chloroplasts and L17 from eukaryotes.
The N-terminal domain appears to be specific to the  eukaryotic ribosomal proteins L25, L23, and L23a.
Ribosomal_L26 is a family of the 50S and the 60S ribosomal proteins from eukaryotes - L26 - and archaea - L25.
This family has been extended to coincide with ref [1]. The KOW (Kyprides, Ouzounis, Woese) motif is found in a variety of ribosomal proteins and NusG.
pfam_descriptions: Ribosomal proteins L26 eukaryotic, L24P archaeal

pfam_comments: The N-terminal region of the eukaryotic ribosomal L27 has the KOW motif.  C-terminal region is represented by this family.
This presumed domain is found at the N-terminus of Ribosomal L30 proteins and has been termed RL30NT or NUC018 [1].
This family includes prokaryotic L30 and eukaryotic L7.

This family includes: Ribosomal L7A from metazoa, Ribosomal L8-A and L8-B from fungi, 30S ribosomal protein HS6 from archaebacteria, 40S ribosomal protein S12 from eukaryotes, Ribosomal protein L30 from eukaryotes and archaebacteria. Gadd45 and MyD118 [1].
This family includes ribosomal protein L32 from eukaryotes and archaebacteria.
This family includes ribosomal protein L37 from eukaryotes and archaebacteria. The family contains many conserved cysteines and histidines suggesting that this protein may bind to zinc.
Bovine L40 has been identified as a secondary RNA binding protein [1]. L40 is fused to a ubiquitin protein [2].

This family contains a number of ubiquitin-like proteins: SUMO (smt3 homologue) (see Swiss:Q02724), Nedd8 (see Swiss:P29595), Elongin B (see Swiss:Q15370), Rub1 (see Swiss:Q9SHE7), and Parkin (see Swiss:O60260). A number of them are thought to carry a distinctive five-residue motif termed the proteasome-interacting motif (PIM), which may have a biologically significant role in protein delivery to proteasomes and recruitment of proteasomes to transcription sites [5].
This ribosomal protein is found in archaebacteria and eukaryotes. It contains four conserved cysteine residues that may bind to zinc.
This is a family of ribosomal proteins, 60S L18 from eukaryotes and 50S L18e from Archaea.

pfam_descriptions: Ribosomal Proteins L2, RNA binding domain
